1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,810
You can't even fool a dog.

2
00:00:01,920 --> 00:00:09,250
Your mannerisms, eyes, facial expressions, all spell P-H-O-N-Y when you pretend.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:15,330
Now, when I'm gathering information about a prospect, I do what every other agent does.

4
00:00:15,520 --> 00:00:21,010
I get his age, where he works, how much he makes, how many kids he's got, and so on.

5
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:25,490
But I also get something else, which most salesmen never search for.

6
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:29,649
That is, some sound reasons why I can like the prospect.

7
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,450
Maybe the job he's doing will supply the reason, or perhaps I can find it someplace in his past record.

8
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:39,490
But I find some good reasons to like him.

9
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:46,129
Then, whenever my attention is focused on the prospect, I review the reasons why I like him.

10
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:52,290
I build a likable image of the prospect before I say one word to him about insurance.

11
00:00:52,800 --> 00:00:54,530
This little technique works.

12
00:00:54,720 --> 00:00:58,290
Because I like him, he sooner or later likes me.

13
00:00:58,560 --> 00:01:04,129
Pretty soon, instead of sitting across the table from him, I'm on the same side with him,

14
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:07,169
and we're working out his insurance plan together.

15
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:11,889
He trusts and believes in my judgment because I am a friend.

16
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:19,490
Now, people don't always accept me right off the bat, but I've found that so long as I continue to like a fellow,

17
00:01:19,599 --> 00:01:22,609
he'll come around and we can get down to business.

18
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:29,250
Just last week, my friend went on, I was making the third call on a difficult prospect.

19
00:01:29,440 --> 00:01:35,250
He met me at the door, and before I could even say good evening, he proceeded to give me hell.

20
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:40,930
He went on and on, not even stopping for a breath until he had run down and finished with,

21
00:01:41,119 --> 00:01:43,570
and don't ever come back here again.

22
00:01:44,480 --> 00:01:49,889
After he had said that, I just stood there looking into his eyes for about five seconds,

23
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:55,970
and then said softly and with genuine sincerity, because I meant it, but Mr. S,

24
00:01:56,160 --> 00:01:58,609
I'm calling tonight as your friend.

25
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:04,210
Yesterday, he bought a $250,000 endowment policy.

26
00:02:06,320 --> 00:02:11,010
Sol Polk is popularly called the appliance king of Chicago.

27
00:02:11,119 --> 00:02:19,169
Starting with nothing, Sol Polk now sells millions of dollars worth of appliances in a year in metropolitan Chicago.

28
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:24,530
Sol Polk credits a lot of his success to his attitude toward shoppers.

29
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:30,050
Customers, says Mr. Polk, should be treated like they are guests in my home.

30
00:02:30,320 --> 00:02:32,930
Isn't that thinking toward people?

31
00:02:33,040 --> 00:02:37,169
And isn't it about the simplest success formula one can put to work?

32
00:02:37,440 --> 00:02:40,530
Just treat customers like guests in your home.

33
00:02:41,119 --> 00:02:44,210
This technique works outside the store too.

34
00:02:44,400 --> 00:02:52,530
Substitute the word employees for customers so that it reads, employees should be treated like guests in my home.

35
00:02:52,880 --> 00:02:59,490
Give first class treatment to your employees and you get first class cooperation, first class output.

36
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:05,889
Think first class about everyone around you and you'll receive first class results in return.

